I recently discovered the joys of the Sublime Text 2 text editor and decided to whip up syntax highlighting and auto completion to round off the editor.  
All of the items on the OpenSCAD cheat sheet have been added to the auto completion system and you can tab between the fields. For example typing: "cu" will pop up "cube([width], [height], [depth])" press enter and the cursor will automatically be in the width field. Tab through the rest and it will deposit you outside the brackets.  
I use the Monakai Dark color scheme so thats why I went with fusha, seafoam and white. Makes for some dramatic looking files.  
INSTRUCTIONS:

1) Download Sublime Text 2.0.2:
http://www.sublimetext.com/2 2) In the editor: Preferences -> Browse Packages... 3) Extract the zip, it will make a folder called OpenSCAD. Restart the editor.

This arrow fletching jig is a remix of thing 578962. See http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:578962 I made this jig mostly to straight-fletch long shafts with 5" feathers for my slingbow but it works fine for other bows and arrow launchers too. Changes:

  • Enlarged tool to support 5" feathers.

  • Base arm hinges extended and joined for greater strength.

  • Loading wedge added. (Insert and push wedge into slot from arm backside to spread slot open and ease the loading of feather into arm.)

  • V4 base uses removable tapered nock index inserts. Use needle nose pliers to insert, push, and twist the insert into the base at the desired indexed nock angle.

  • Nock insert with and without slot is provided.

  • Two arms with different size center relief grooves provided for ~5/16" ("312") and ~11/32 shafts ("360"). Arms support straight fletching only.

Both printed on Garolite at 250 C nozzle temperature with Kisslicer raft AND 0.60 mm thick fillet brim, which are both necessary to achieve perfect nylon to bed adhesion with these thick and blocky parts. Build chamber was heated to 30C. Nylon is perfect for this application because it's somewhat flexible, strong, and resistant to fletching adhesive. It is, however, perhaps the most challenging material to print well! Support was useful (but not absolutely mandatory in nylon), for the overhangs of the base hinge arm screw holes only.

It's always tricky and time-consuming to edit mesh files instead of solid models! Nonetheless, I used Wings 3D to push and pull mesh surfaces and Blender boolean ops to combine with new geometries created in netfabb Studio and Geomagic.

How is this an atom? Every atom is composed of a nucleus and one or more electrons bound to the nucleus. The nucleus is made of one or more protons and typically a similar number of neutrons (none in hydrogen-1). Protons and neutrons are called nucleons. Over 99.94% of the atom's mass is in the nucleus. The protons have a positive electric charge, the electrons have a negative electric charge, and the neutrons have no electric charge. If the number of protons and electrons are equal, that atom is electrically neutral. If an atom has more or fewer electrons than protons, then it has an overall negative or positive charge, respectively, and it is called an ion.

This is a mount for classic Rostock 3D printer to allow quick change of hot-ends and other tools on your printer. I took the idea from RichRap Quick-Fit But it's not compatible because Rostock platform is smaller than RichRap's Quick-Fit carriages. Design created in OpenJSCAD.org

• print all parts - holder-1, holder-2, latch, key
  • print mount-template or develop your own mount based on provided .SCAD file or .STL
  • use MR105 ZZ Model Miniature Ball Bearing 5X10X4 for the latch
  • use 4 M4 screws and standard holes in Rostock platform to assemble it
    • Universal E3D / J-Head mount can be used with E3D or J-Head ver 5-6 hot-ends
  • print qf-jhead-e3d-mount-plate.stl and qf-jhead-e3d-lock.stl
  • insert PTFE (4mm) into the center hole
  • attach M4 nut to the tube and push the nut down into the mount
  • insert hot-end
  • use one of two holes to lock the hot-end , use lower hole for E3D or another one for J-Head
    • qf-jhead-e3d-mount.scad provided for modifications.

The MK6+ is great, but the stock configuration assumes the filament's diameter remains constant.  If the filament gets thinner, the pressure will drop off rapidly and extrusion will stop.  If it gets thicker, steps will be missed, loud noises will be made, and extrusion will slow down.  Either situation can cause a ruined or weakened output.  I was tired of having to babysit it, and I had two extra springs in my Wade's hardware kit, so I designed this spring adapter.
Before I installed it, my MK6+ would print for around 30 minutes, on average, before needing tightening or loosening.  Since I've installed it, I've printed for more than eight hours without intervening.  It took my machine from "high maintenance" to "fire and forget."

Note: This design is for the MK6+ with 3 mm filament. I will upload one for 1.75 mm as soon as I have a chance to do it. Also, make sure the adapter is not heated up by the motor. In my case the stock fan works well for that. Print the adapter. In the recess inside the adapter, install a spring like the ones included in UltiMachine's Wade's Extruder Hardware Kit. Remove the thumbgrip from the plunger screw (or use another equivalent screw, but still with the nut on it). Bolt the adapter onto the MK6 top end, over the screw, so that the spring presses on the screw. It's much easier if there's no filament in the extruder. Adjust the screw so that it moves the plunger in further than it could if filament were present, but not all the way to the drive wheel. I used needle-nosed pliers. Thread filament under power (with the motor running). I had to cut it at an angle and use a good deal of force to get the plunger to move out of the way, but you might not have to if you are willing to adjust it more than I am. Enjoy lower-maintenance printing!

description.text: A spacer to allow old or second hand 7" vinyl with a broken-out centre piece to be played on turntables with a narrow spindle.

I got some of these really nice spacers from Monorail Records, Glasgow, and have wanted to make a printable version for some time as I wasn't too keen on the vinyl spacers on Thingiverse already (really big parts - lots of unnecessary plastic). I scanned the original (the best way to ensure the photo is taken square on - the scan is the default image above) and imported this image (as a .jpg) into SketchUp where I traced out the shape as best as possible using primitive shapes and arcs for the trickier details.  
The SketchUp model was a bit of a mess (I only include it here for completeness) and the original .stl file had some errors in it. I cleared these up in Netfabb and printed a first test version, which was slightly too small to fit the gap in the 7". A quick measurement and calculation later, I scaled the model to 107% and it works great! I printed a bed full (7x on a Printrbot Jr - how many can you get in one go?) after seeing that the model worked nicely.

UPDATE: The bolt assembly does work. I got the pieces back out and finally printed the threaded hub and bolt for a glue-less assembly. One thing to note, the orientation of the hub is important. There is one receiving notch that is slightly closer to the center. This is the bottom notch meant to hold the base of the tree topper. If it isn't in the right spot the holes won't line up. The bolt itself could use some tweaking for aesthetics. Maybe trim down the height of the bolt head or make it blend in with the medallion. Would love to see what others come up with.
My wife looked at the bare top of our tree and said, "Why don't you PRINT us a star?" I searched her words for a hint of sarcasm, but she is a kind person and was being sincere. Still, I thought it was a chance to prove my little hobby that consumes some money and lots of time was actually useful for something other than printing nerd props and junky toys.
This model is still being printed, so the jury is still out. I just thought I'd go ahead and upload the models while it bakes. All together I estimate 10 hours of printing on my Flashforge Creator. I'm only about 4 hours into it. I'll let you know how it turns out. 
UPDATE: The cover pic is the finished product. Only I already updated the "medallion" to have a hole in the center so that it will be compatible with my version 2 base which will have threading to receive a bolt to hold everything together with no glue. I'll add the revised files when I get a chance.

description.text:
I really liked the Open Brushless Gimbal, however I wanted 3-Axis. I re-drew the entire model and made the following changes over the original. Tweaked the Lengths of the arms so that my Go-Pro Hero 3 Black would balance. Changed the main Arm to accept a brushless motor. For the Yaw-Axis I am using the RC Timer Brushless motor (link below) Changed the Suspension Frame to have a pass-through for the slip-ring wires. Changed the hole spacing so that it will fit the RC-Timer motor (run a countersink bit over the motor side of the center hole for better clearance). Changed it from 4 to 6 dampeners to compensate for the extra weight. Changed the Go-Pro box so that it has a more complete fit (I was concerned the Go-Pro could be ejected in flight). I tried making locking/release tabs, however they immediatly broke. It's held in pretty good by friction. I am not 100% satisfied with the design, I will likely tweak it. The hole-pattern on the box needs to be tweaked so that pitch is balanced, this is also on my future to-do list. A note about roll-arm balancing. There is about 3mm play that the pitch motor can be slid in and out. This can be used to set the balance of the roll perfectly. Keep the screw somewhat loose so that you can move the motor around until you get the perfect balance, than tighten up the screw. Link to the Motor I am using for the Yaw Axis...
Rctimer 2608-70T Brushless Gimbal Motor With Slip Ring(12N14P): http://rctimer.com/product-1339.html If anyone improves the design, please share it so we can all benifit. I have not tested this in flight, I feel the design is sound, however as with anything free, use this at your own discretion. In other-words, don't blame me if you lose a go-pro in flight or any other issues you experience due to a design problem. All credit is due turbi for his original design, without it, I wouldn't have had such a great base to build from.

This is my take of a cyclonic separator that I found on the web http://woodgears.ca/reader/walters/cyclone.html as designed by Ronald Walters made of balsa wood. Much respect for taking the time to make this out of wood strips but I don't have that kind of patience. I "whitewashed" it with acetone to slick it over to improve strength at the layers. I added a cyclonic ridge to give to a bit more air circulation. Maybe it helps maybe it was just for fun. Also the side vent is closed for printing purposes to improve print quality as sometimes I find large openings will have a layer or two lift causing cracks. Support is designed into the file. I have included the solidworks file so that you may adapt it to your hoses. I was greatly impressed with its function and am hopeful to never buy another filter again.
